segments.text: establishment.
Where was it and how big was it?
Well, it's just on the other side of the Brazos River Bridge at Highway 60.
And it was just probably no more than a 20 by 30 size building.
It was a relatively small place.
And it was the closest place to Galley Station to buy liquor.
It was right across the county line in whatever county that is.
Burleson.
Burleson County.
What else did it offer for sale other than liquor?
Well, beer and liquor.
And that's maybe, you know, some jerky and the usual kind of stuff like that.
No gas station or anything like that?
No, no.
It was just a liquor store.
And was open?
Well, I guess whatever the hours allowed under state law, I'm sure it was open full time.
But the woman that ran it, she was still there when I came back as a faculty member.
It was the same woman.
Did you ever hear of a bootlegger in Brazos County?
I never have.
No.
I'm sure there were, but I didn't know about them.
There were, you know, there was a place out on, we heard about, that was out on the Brazos River that was supposedly a plantation that ran, you know, prostitutes and gambling.
Great.
We never did know exactly where that was, but it was one of those things you heard about.
I think that had been there during the Bryan Air Force days.
Oh, okay.
Whether it still was or not, I don't know.
Yeah, I don't know either.
All right, how often did anybody bring liquor back to the dorm, be it beer or hard liquor?
I guess frequently.
I said that in the dorm we were in, they would take the medicine cabinet out of the wall, and there was a hollow space in there, and there were pipes, because the sink was right below it.
And they could hang the liquor, put a string around a heavy nylon line around the bottle, and they'd drop it down where you couldn't see it.
And one time, I think the story was that somebody dropped one down too far.
And of course, they took it out, and it was from above, and it got caught.
So you had to hang it just about right.
Did anybody ever go in and steal somebody else's while they weren't in the room?
I don't know.
I'm sure it probably happened.
Do you remember anybody getting caught by an inspection officer?
Well, I never actually witnessed it, but I had heard that people had gotten caught.
Let's see, back to dorm life, what about some jokes, some pranks, some good bull that you, during those two years that you heard of?
Oh, yeah, yeah.
There was always something that would go on.
Describe some of that.
One of the better ones was this guy that, his name was Hubert, Earl Hubert, and he was an upperclassman, and he

he was was sort of the officious I guess might be a good way of describing his nickname was Earl the girl because he had sort of effeminate behaviors and Earl kept his keys on a on a chain you know and the chain was gonna go in his pocket and he would come up and unlock the door to his to his dorm room and with this key you know and it would still be attached to him and and so
I wasn't actually in on doing it, but they got a bicycle inner tube and they tied it to the radiator.
And then they used to take the end of a Coke carton and you saw the metal or wooden Coke cartons that carried the Coke bottles and they saw a thing and they were called
fuck sticks because you could lock somebody in your dorm room with them.

Well, they took one of those and put it on, they tied the bicycle inner tube to that and then, you know, stretched it and closed the door so that when Earl came up and stuck his key in and turned it, of course, it just, it took his belt off.
And he got very upset about that.
And another thing, and I was in on this, we moved his dorm room, all of his furniture to the shower and set it up inside the shower.
And that was a thing that happened occasionally.
What about anybody you hear of, an animal put into their room?
Yeah, we got a bunch of dead rabbits one time, put them in somebody's room.
Put them in a place where they weren't going to be found for a little while, up in the top of the closet, as I recall.
Of course, they really started stinking in a day or so.
Now, where did the rabbits come from?
Where did anybody get the dead rabbits?
Well, at that time, they had a program in the 60s where they killed off all the coyotes, and they paid ranchers and trappers to kill them, and they had this explosion of,
of rabbits and rats.
And, hey, you could go out on the road and, you know, about every ten feet there'd be a dead rabbit.
It was amazing.
There was one period in there was, you know.
But, yeah, there were lots of dead rabbits you could find and roadkill, basically.
Another good thing that they would do would be to babble bomb somebody.
And you would, you know,
You'd take the light bulb out of the room.
There's just one big light up in the room.
You could have a desk lamp.
There's one big light bulb.
You'd take that out and screw in a thing where you could plug a wire in, an extension cord.

And then you would fray the ends of the extension cord and with the light off, you know, wrap them together and stick them down inside of a, which you could buy at that time, like M-80s or cherry bombs.
And then you put that inside of a can of Babbo or one guy, they did it with pepper and I think he ended up in the hospital, you know.
And this was in the animal company downstairs, E2.
And of course, you go in, you turn the light on, this rather powerful firecracker, in fact, they're outlawed, you can't even buy them today, would go off and blow Babbo,
or the one-case pepper all over the room.
And, of course, it meant the freshmen then had to come and clean the room up, you know, and get rid of all this bad, which just went absolutely everywhere, you know.
And then another thing that happened would be they would flood out dormitories.
You got to go to...
But they would flood out the dormitories.
Now, this never happened, but there were stories that they would...

know take all the tops off the toilets and water and this happened the year before i came and apparently people were still talking about it and they sort of filled the dormitory up with uh with water and you know you got to wonder why the university would allow this to go on you know and of course maybe they because you got to have done tremendous damage to the buildings you know plumbing and wiring and and everything in fact i think there was a very strong prohibition against
doing that.

One of the other dorms in that area did get flooded out and some of them would go into the steam tunnels and turn the water off to the building and then go in and take the tops off all the toilets and then go back down the steam tunnel and turn the water back on.
Now, do you have any idea how, where they got into the steam tunnels?
Well, there was a space in each where it came up into the dormitory.
And it was in a closet that somebody had a key to.
Did you ever go into a steam tunnel?
No, I never did.
Did you know where the entrance was?
Well, there were some outside ones, too, where you could take the lid off.
Like a manhole cover?
Actually, more like a piece of plate steel was laying there.
And you could see steam coming out of them at times, literally, in the right weather conditions.
Do these tunnels still exist, as far as you know?
I guess.
I don't know.
Somebody told me that
that they had a lot of trouble with the buildings all along what was military walk, because there used to be a steam tunnel that went under that street.
And when they tore the street out, they closed that in and filled in that steam tunnel.
And it all created a real drainage problem.
And that's between YMCA and academic and all of that, which was that when I came here as a faculty member, it was still a street.
Were there ever any pranks at mealtime?
Yeah.
There were, you know, individual things where one upperclassman would get a freshman to do something to another upperclassman's food or something like that.
Or the other thing was that there was always a military officer that ate in the dining hall and kind of sat over on a table.
I think it was a little bit elevated.
And I always wondered how the guy felt, you know.
I mean, there eating by yourself.
And occasionally there'd be another officer with him, but generally this guy's there by themselves.
And occasionally what they would do is that on some command everybody would stand up and throw a bread roll over to this and hit this guy.
And he took it with, I guess, a certain degree of affection.
We really didn't hate him quite as bad as he might have thought or something.
I don't know.
And then there were other kinds of things on people's birthdays where things would do it.
And there was an animal guy.
In fact, that was his nickname, Animal, that was in E2.
And there was this three-legged dog that ran around campus called Tripod.
And I think it was probably a
like a mixed golden retriever or Irish setter, something like that, the color of it.
It was a big red dog with his left front leg missing.
And Tripod got around just fine on the three legs.
he would come into Sabisa Dining Hall and this guy would sit him in a chair next to him at the table and he would eat.
And nobody said anything.
It's kind of amazing.
And let's see, and Ranger was around then, Mr. Rutter's dog.
Right, he was, yeah.
Describe.
He was an English bulldog with a brachycephalic skull, a pushed in thing.
And the youngest rudder boy used to come over.
And he was a real kind of pest, as boys about 9 or 10 can be.
And he was just looking for attention, I guess.
He probably had no playmates on the campus.
And he would come over with Ranger.
And of course Ranger would bark at people and you know.
Ann Rutter told me, in fact, that dog, they had a place out at Carter Lake, and he walked off the end of the pier and couldn't swim and apparently drowned, was the end of Ranger.
And then he was buried over there.
Oh, really?
Oh, his grave's still marked.
Really, where?
Out there in front of the President's House.
Is that?
There's a little bitty.
Oh, is that right?
Yes.
That I didn't know.
I noticed that.
Oh, okay.
Over by where the old President's House was.
No, no, no, no.
Oh, the new president's house.
The new president's house.
Oh, that's right, because they would have burned it in 63 and Ranger died later on.
As you go by you'll see four little posts and there's a little kind of a rope.
I guess I've seen that.
I didn't know what that was.
That's Ranger's Lass.
Can he see the scoreboard?
I don't think.
Did you all ever attempt to play any tricks on faculty members in class or anything?
No.
I don't ever hear of anybody doing that.
The only thing that even, and this wasn't a trick, but I took organic chemistry and we worked on this lab project for ages and, you know, I mean like two lab periods.
In the end, obviously, something went wrong.
The thing foamed up, and it went all over the bench and everything.
And so we had to turn in this precipitate that we got in the end.
And so we looked at what other people had, and we went over and found something on the shelf.
And we said, yeah, that's it.
So we put it into the bottle, and we turned it in.
And the next lab period, this guy is Rakoff.
He says, you know, halter?
I want to see you for a minute.
And he said, what the hell did you all put in that bottle?
And we just played innocent.
We had to redo the experiment on our own time.
We always imagined that he probably had something he poured into it, tested it, and it had to turn some color or do something.
And he poured it in and it blew up in his face.
That's what we expected, maybe.
What did you and your friends come to believe were the general guidelines about class attendance and class behavior and so forth at A&M?
Well, attendance was something you did.
You didn't miss class, you know.
Now there were people who would do that, but by and large I think the class attendance was, and the expectations were that,
If you were called on in some classes, you'd stand up to answer.
Like military science classes, you had to pop to attention if you were called on to answer a question.
I don't think other classes did that.
But it was the expectation where you shut up and you behaved yourself.
But I don't know that there was ever any problem.
I don't remember there being behavior anymore than there are today.
Occasionally, you have people who
who act up in class, but what I found is the other students generally discipline them, and you don't have to really do very much.
Do you remember anybody getting in trouble for going to sleep?
Oh, yeah, including me.
What happened?
Well, I had to stand up the rest of the class period.
You'd never get away with that today, I suspect.
How did you, that first semester, how did you come out academically here?
Oh, I didn't do very well.

I think part of it was, you know, there was I guess a lot of the stuff, the hazing you took personally, you know, and you probably shouldn't have, but you know, I don't know, it just wasn't my character I guess to, and there was a lot of crap that went on, you know.
Did you think about leaving?
Yeah.
Why didn't you?
Well, if you wanted to be a veterinarian, you had to go to A&M.
So you came back the next year.
So was the spring semester better?
Oh, yeah, I don't think there was any question about spring, you know, coming back.
And, you know, coming back the next year may have been more the question, you know.
But I came back for, you know, my third year in college.
And when did you begin to think about something other than veterinary medicine?
I think it's when it's obvious that you weren't doing well enough in the science classes.
I never caught on to organic chemistry, and that was a real weed-out course for vet school.
And some of the other anatomy things that you had to do, and somehow an animal soaked in formaldehyde that you had to cut up just wasn't my idea of a lot of fun.
And you knew that in vet school, it was a quarter section of a horse that you had to work on.
Because a horse is, I don't know, it's still the basis of anatomy.
I don't know, it was just a lot of that.

Also, you know, when I went home like in the summer, and other times I worked for this veterinarian in Wichita Falls, and the more I saw what you did as a veterinarian, and you know, it really was hard work.
You know, and I think at that time you got $15 for a spay or neutering of an animal.
A lot of work for not much money.

And I remember one afternoon, we were at a long operation, and it's hot, you know, Wichita Falls is summer, sweating, and you think, man, I kind of wish this animal would die so I can get the hell out of here.
That's probably not the attitude you need if you're going to be a veterinary.
That second year, did you have some classes, some instructors that were important?
Yeah, well, I think you were, as I said, as a Civil War class.
Why did a pre-vet take a course in that?
I don't know.
I changed my major, you know, to history and political science.
What led you to make that change?
I think I just always enjoyed history.
And I had Blue Book Benton for government, as it was called back then, state and local government, 207.
the first course, American National Government at Midwestern from John Tower.
And then Tower described Professor John Tower.
Well, Professor John Tower is only about three feet tall.
Most people don't know.
He's not that short.
No, I know.
He's five foot something.
He's a very short guy.
And he was very cocky.
He, you know, had these really immaculate suits that he wore to class and he had this fedora hat that he would come in with it on.
impeccably dressed, and it was quite a sort of show.
And he had by that point been converted to republicanism, and that in itself was sort of a surprise.
And I think he was, a lot of what he said and did, I don't think I realize it, was very political.
in his approach to things.
Now, he was a full-time faculty member.
Yes.
Was that, I guess, a lecture?
I don't know.
In hindsight, was it obvious that he was aiming for elected
No, it was not.
It was not obvious at all.
But the next year, he did.
I guess it was 61, wasn't it?
Because, yeah, special election, 1961.
So I was here at A&M.
Describe his capability as a
as a teacher, as a lecturer?
Oh, he was interesting.
He was engaging, you know, and kept your attention.
He told lots of stories.
He had run for the legislature as a Democrat sometime in the 50s.
Of course, there weren't any Republicans in Wichita County at that time except his father-in-law, Orville Bullington.
who ran for governor in 32 against Ma Ferguson as a Republican, did rather well.
And he was an oil man, came down from Pennsylvania and bought his Republican, this is Orville Bullington.
Centaur, after he married Bunny Bullington, his first wife,
really, I guess, began the conversion to Republicanism.
And I think his father-in-law was a big influence on him.
He told lots of interesting stories about politics.
And he'd run for the state legislature along with another guy that ran

They campaigned together, and I don't remember now which seats they were in for, but the guy worked for Lyndon Johnson and was caught in a homosexual encounter, remember, in a restroom during the 64 campaign.
What is that guy's name?
Anyway, worked for Lyndon Johnson, went back to Austin after that and worked at KLBJ I think.
I'll think of his name anyway.
How would, as you think back, how would you rank John Tower's intellectual, was it a good solid course?
I think so, yeah.
Was he politically biased?
Oh yeah.
But did your answers have to be biased?
Well, I think they were, I don't know that they had to be.
He gave a kind of a cross between short answer and multiple guess and matching type.
How rigorous was the course?
I didn't find it very hard, but I guess I had a talent or an ability in that area, not in organic chemistry.
All right, now you and I both know that Gene Benton was a legendary teacher here.
You're the first person I've interviewed yet that had him in class, so supply as much information for the future about Gene Benton as the teacher from a student's point of view.
Gene was very interesting.
He's a walking encyclopedia of Texas government.
His first book, which I have at home, I have most of the other editions here, to a large degree was ripped off by a lot of the other Texas government textbook people.
It's amazing if you go and look at all of these, how many of them are simply quoting other books in Texas government.
I mean, there's no primary source, and some of them are really bad academically.
And they rely upon Benton for their information.
And so here you have the guy that's teaching the class.
He wrote the book, which really helped a lot.
And I basically went through and outlined the book in great detail.
His lectures, when he would lecture, he never looked at the students.
He always looked in another direction or something else.
If you asked him a question, he would momentarily look you directly in the eye.
But he would stand there and talk for the entire 50 minutes, just a constant.
stream of information and really, I say, encyclopedic knowledge of aspects of the Texas legislature.
You go back and look at the first edition.
Later editions, and I expect it was editorial changes, weren't quite that way, weren't quite as legalistic, detailed.
God, I mean the footnotes in that first book are just incredible, the detailed information.
Kind of a, almost a Milton Nance kind of, the Mere Expedition type, you know what I mean, by that detail and footnoting and things, yeah.
But, you know, I, a lot of people really didn't like him because, you know, he spoke in almost a monotone and he didn't look, but there was a lot of information coming out there.
Any humor?
Very little.
And did he tolerate any pranks or jokes or any student not paying attention?
I don't think anybody would have dared do that, you know.
I mean, he had a reputation of being a, I mean, his nickname was Blue Buck Benton.
Yeah, I know, but this machine doesn't.
Why was he Blue Buck Benton?
He would say, well, the exam will be Thursday of next week.
Bring two blue books.
And the expectations were that you filled up a couple of blue books answering the questions.
It was right like hell, basically.
If you didn't have, if you forgot your blue book, what happened?
I never did.
I don't know of anybody that ever did.
I used to tell students, I still do, I say, if you forget your blue book, I will have some available for sale in class on that day, and they cost three dollars each.
How rigorous was the course?
It was very rigorous.
I made a B in it.
I felt I deserved an A.
But I don't know that Gene gave A's.
Maybe he did.
And I had one of the better grades in the class.
And he didn't grade on the curve.
I don't know that he did, no.
I don't think so.
And, you know, back then, 92 and above was an A, you know, so you could have a 90 and, you know.
But he didn't give numerical grades, as I remember he gave, like pluses and minuses, A minus, B plus, and so on.
Did you ever have many conversations with him out of class about political science and so forth?
No.
He wasn't real approachable.
And I think that was true via accurate observation when I came back as a faculty member, you know, that he didn't
He didn't interact much with the students.
He was not here much except during office hours, and he was faithful to that.
There was absolutely nothing in his office.
Maybe a phone book and nothing else.
And that was because I didn't know at the time, but later on he told me that when he was a faculty member at SMU, where he taught John Tower, incidentally,

that John Birchers decided he was a communist, and they went to his office looking for evidence that he was a communist in the Bircher-McCarthy days, and so he never kept anything in his office, which I found peculiar.
Were his lectures objective?
I think so, but probably with a liberal bent would be my evaluation.
I'm not real sure I was sophisticated enough to pick up on those things at the time.
And I must admit, I remember coming home and saying some things around my father who once had a picture of Roosevelt on the wall.
We did not have candles and a kneeling rail, but we could have.
And saying some things about Roosevelt or the Democrats or something like that, and getting quite a reaction from my father, and I didn't do that again.
What?
Stuff that John Tower had said in class.
Oh, oh, oh.
You know, and so I come home and say, well, Professor Tower says.

It's really interesting in this, there's this thing in here about can Bush be elected and there's the Hispanic from San Antonio that has the big huge advertising firm and he's one of the people that they're quoting and this is really interesting because I had this same experience.
He says here,
this is Lionel Sosa, was preteen when an independent street
with his father brought home a television set for the family in San Antonio in 1952.
When he turned it on, the Republicans were anointing Dwight David Eisenhower as a nominee for president.
The youngster was mesmerized.
My parents said, Lionel, you can't be like Reich.
He's a Republican.
The 61-year-old Sosa remembers today, we've always been Democrats.
Republicans are the party of the rich, and we're the poor.
And the Democrats are the party of the poor.
I said, well, then who the hell wants to be poor?
And that's why I was rebelling.
Well, I remember having a very similar experience, and this is in Oklahoma City in 1952.
And I came home with an I Like Ike button on, which somebody had given me at school.
And my grandmother gave me this lecture about we don't wear those kinds of things.
and removed the button.
As you look back on it, did Gene Benton for you become a kind of an intellectual role model?
I don't think so.
Political science, a faculty member?
Maybe to some degree, yeah.
I hadn't really decided on political science at that point.
In fact, I really didn't.
until I decided to go to graduate school.
As an undergraduate, I got a double major in history and political science.
And it was kind of a decision about which way do you go.
And I think part of the experience I had at Midwestern with some of the faculty members that really encouraged me to go on to graduate school was maybe why I went in that direction.
All right.
Here, that second year, whom did you turn to for academic advice?
Well, for you, to a large degree, about, you know, I still remember you talking about, I was already considering graduate school.
Remember you told me you need to go to the best graduate school your time and abilities will get you into, and time, abilities, and money will get you into.
And, you know, I did a master's degree at Midwestern.
And part of it, you know, you had a pretty low academic fall at A&M.
And then you have to dig your way out of that, you know, which you managed to do at Midwestern.
And I guess the redemption, and that included going on to graduate school.
And then you had enough whatever to do, do well enough on the GRE and enough grades and recommendations to get into graduate school.
Now, that second year here, do you remember what you, you went your sophomore and junior year here.
Do you remember what your GPA was when you left?
Right around a 2.0.
Well, 1.0 back then.
Oh, yeah, yeah, about 2.0.
About 2.0 by today's standards.
And so you had changed your major.
Anybody else you turned to for advice?
Was there an associate dean or an assistant dean?
No.
I do remember meeting with Hubert when I changed my major.
He was, I think, dean of arts and sciences at that point.
Do you describe that?
I don't remember much about it, but I just remember, and then years later when I came back,
for an interview for the faculty position, I met with the same guy.
I don't think I mentioned that to him.
All right.
Describe the MSC and its role for an undergraduate during your years here.
What was the MSC?
What did that mean to you?
Well, we'd go over there maybe in the afternoons to have coffee or something like that.
And I got interested and involved with SCONA my junior year.
How did that come about?
just interest in politics.
And here's a program that's bringing in political speakers from outside.
